BCM963XX Application Note Introduction to Broadcom Execution Environment Platform
Chapter 1: Introduction
This document introduces the Broadcom Execution Environment Platform (BEEP) and the Broadcom Execution
Environment (BEE).
BEEP is a service platform framework that enables services to be dynamically deployed into the gateway. BEEP contains a
bus system and virtualization software framework to facilitate the modular software function. BEEP offers security features,
such as verifying package integrity and ensuring privacy of the services.
The management of modular software is based on Broadband Forum TR-157 (Documents). The data models supported are
TR-98 or TR-181. Different specifications refer to software modules in different terms; such as bundles, software packages,
and deployment unit, but they all mean the same and are used interchangeably in this document.
1.1 Scope
This document contains high level descriptions of BEEP and BEE. Refer to the specifications in Documents for more details
on the standards. There is a more detailed developers guide (CPE-BEEP-AN10X) that can be requested through
Broadcoms BCA marketing.

BCM963XX Application Note Introduction to Broadcom Execution Environment Platform
In the Broadband Forum standard, HG_EE is the Execution Environment (EE) and Portable Module is a Deployment Unit
(DU). A deployment unit can consist of any number of libraries, configuration files, and executable programs.
The Broadcom Execution Environment Platform supports four different execution environments (EE):
OSGi
OpenWRT
Docker
Broadcom Execution Environment (BEE)
The BEEP allows the execution environments to be installable, update-able, and un-installable. In 5.02L04, the BEE is the
EE that supports all operations. Deployment Units (software module or packages) are installable, update-able, and
un-installable in BEE via TR157.

Chapter 3: Benefits of Modular Software
Modular software provides the following benefits to the carriers home gateway:
Avoids frequent firmware upgrades.
Provides quick resolution to security issues.
Offers flexibility in deploying the services.
Avoids a long cycle of verification.
Upgrades services without impacting the basic broadband functionality, including bug fixes, upgrades, and new
features.
Provides the ability to communicate with nomadic clients, smart phones, pads, notebooks, and so on.
Provides the ability to communicate with and control Internet of Things (IoT) devices at home.
Allows third-party services to run in an isolated Execution Environment that communicates with its own cloud network.

Chapter 4: Basic Blocks of the BEEP
The figure below illustrates the Broadcom Execution Environment Platform (BEEP) with the execution environments in it.
Figure 4: Execution Environments of BEEP
The Broadcom Execution Environment Platform (BEEP) consists of the Service Platform framework and one or more
instances of Execution Environments. The BEEP framework consists of a bus and the Service Platform Daemon (SPD).
Broadcom reference software provides the Broadcom Execution Environment (BEE). The other EEs available are OSGi,
OpenWRT, and Docker.
4.1 Bus
The bus is a transport for the platform daemon to communicate with execution environments. It is the transport for
applications in execution environments to communicate with each other. Services offered by one execution environment can
be consumed by another execution environment. The bus gate of the BEEP framework guarantees the protection of private
services and the security of signals that only get sent to and received by authorized recipients. Applications can consume
services provided by the interface implementation provided by server applications only when it has the permission to do so.
This type of access is specified by the operator in the manifest of the application via the privilege attributes. By default, all
the services (methods and signals) provided in the BEEP are private, which means they are not accessible unless
permission is granted in the manifest at install time. Permission can be added or removed from the Web UI or via ACS after
the client applications are installed successfully in an execution environment.

4.2 Service Platform Daemon (SPD)
The SPD is the program that manages the life cycle of all the execution environments, performs bus management
(admission control), routes messages from the native configuration system to the execution environments, and restricts
resources used by an EE.
In BEEP, the operator is able to install an execution environment, update it, and un-install it. These operations can be initiated
from the Web UI access from the WAN side of the gateway, via TR69 ACS, or from the Broadcom Broadband Commander
(BBC) tool.
For an execution environment to be installable to BEEP, the EE must be packaged with the Broadcom Package Builder. The
EE package consists of a manifest file that describes the EE type (executable or a tarball), the resources it needs, and basic
information about the EE package. EE is normally a tarball type that consists of a root file system, executables, and
configurations. See Chapter 6, Broadcom Package Builder for more details.
EE operation is the same as package or deployment unit operation, as described in the BBF TR-157 specification. The EE
package is downloaded from a server using HTTP/HTTPS.

Chapter 5: Broadcom Execution Environment (BEE)
Broadcom reference software provides the Broadcom Execution Environment (BEE). The BEE is a lightweight execution
environment. It has a root file system, some essential libraries, and basic BusyBox commands. The BEE utilizes an overlay
file system, which provides read/write layers of a working directory for applications to work on, which is overlaid on a
read-only base file system. Applications running in the BEE utilize the same base system; additional dependency not
included in the base is added with the DU package. The BEE allows software packages/deployment units to be installed,
un-installed, and updated. Operators can use TR-069 ACS, WebUI access from WAN, or the Broadcom Broadband
Commander (BBC) tool to perform all the operations.

Chapter 6: Broadcom Package Builder
The Broadcom Package Builder is a host tool provided by Broadcom. Any package that is installed into BEEP or BEE must
be packaged with this tool. The package format is proprietary to Broadcom.
The package builder tool takes three arguments:
-f pkginfo.txt: Specifies the package information file.
-d: Enables debugging.
-a digestAlgorithm: Specifies the digestAlgorithm used to calculate digest for the package.
-o output package name file name: By default, the package name is
pkg_beep_EEName_EEversion_pkgName_pkgVersion.tar.gz.
